Chiefs Tweeted on their official Twitter page on Saturday that their highly successful coach of the late 1980s and early 1990s had died.Chiefs Tweeted: Our deepest condolences to the family &amp; friends of our former coach Jeff Butler after passing on this morning. May his soul RIP #Khosi4Life The Premier Soccer League have released a statement saying that there will be a moment of silence held in honour of Butler in Saturday s Nedbank Cup quarterfinal between Chiefs and SuperSport United at FNB Stadium (6pm).It read: The Premier Soccer League (PSL) will observe a moment of silence for the late former Kaizer Chiefs and Bafana Bafana coach Jeff Butler. This will apply only at this evening s Nedbank Cup quarterfinal fixture between Kaizer Chiefs and SuperSport United at the FNB Stadium. Butler passed on this (Saturday) morning. The PSL family sends heartfelt condolences to the family of the late Jeff Butler. Butler had a number of stints as Chiefs head coach in 1988 to 1989 1991 1992 and 1995 to 1996.He coached some of Amakhosi s greats and had much trophy-winning success.His 1991 and 1992 Chiefs teams were regarded as among the best seen in South Africa.Spearheaded by the goals of Fani Madida and Shane McGregor with Doctor Khumalo Donald Ace Khuse Neil Tovey Chippa Molatedi Wellington Manyathi and Trevor Mthimkhulu in midfield and Lucas Radebe Howard Freese and Gardner Seale in defence Chiefs cleaned up.They won the league Castle Challenge and BP Top 8 in 1991 and league Top 8 and BobSave SuperBowl in 1992.Butler briefly coached Bafana Bafana after South Africa s readmission to international football in 1992 but was fired after issues over falsifying his CV.- TMG Digital/TMG Sport